'''George Steven Botterill''' (born 8 January 1949) is a Welsh [[chess]] player, writer and philosopher.
Botterill was born in [[Bradford]] and learned chess at the age of seven. From 1969 to 1972 he played for [[Oxford University]], and became one of Britain's leading young players. In 1971 he won the Slater Young Masters tournament at [[Hastings International Chess Congress|Hastings]], and at Hastings 1971/2 he was the top scorer among the British players with 6.0/15. Botterill won the 1974 [[British Chess Championship|British Championship]] at [[Clacton]], winning the playoff at [[Llanelli|Llanelli, Wales]] by a half point over [[William Hartston]] after a seven-way tie for first. In 1977 Botterill won his second British Championship, this time outright.
Botterill won the [[Welsh Chess Championship|Welsh Championship]] in 1973 (jointly). In 1974 he became a lecturer in [[philosophy]] at the [[Aberystwyth University|University of Wales at Aberystwyth]], and began to play for the Welsh international team. In the Preliminary Group of the European Championship he scored 1½–½ against Dutch top board GM [[Jan Timman]] and 1–1 against English top board Hartston. Botterill played first board for [[Wales]] at the 1976 [[Chess Olympiad|Olympiad]] and previously represented England at the World Student Team Championship and [[European Team Chess Championship]] of 1973. He holds the title of International Master.
Botterill is best known as a chess writer, in particular for his [[chess opening]] collaborations with [[Raymond Keene]]: ''The Modern Defence'' (London 1973) and ''The Pirc Defence'' (London 1974). He is currently Senior Lecturer in Philosophy at the [[University of Sheffield]].
