{{Infobox philosopher | region = [[Western philosophy]] | era = [[20th-century philosophy]] and [[contemporary philosophy]] | color = #B0C4DE | image = Nadezda-Cacinovic.jpg | caption = Čačinovič in 2011 | name = Nadežda Čačinovič | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1947|04|01|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Budapest]], [[Republic of Hungary (1946–1949)|Hungarian Republic]] | death_date = | influences = | main_interests = [[Aesthetics]]{{·}}[[Critical theory]]{{·}}[[Feminism]] | spouse = [[Žarko Puhovski]] (divorced) [[Ivo Banac]] (separated) | website = [http://www-wpt.ffzg.hr/filoz/nastavnici/nadezda-cacinovic/ Info and biography] }}
'''Nadežda Čačinovič''' (born 1 April 1947) is a Croatian [[philosophy|philosopher]], [[sociology|sociologist]], [[comparative literature|comparatist]], [[feminism|feminist]] and Croatian-language book author.<ref name="nacional-2007">{{cite web|url=http://www.nacional.hr/clanak/34133/nadezda-cacinovic-europska-karijera-borbene-filozofkinje|title=Nadežda Čačinovič - europska karijera borbene filozofkinje|trans-title=Nadežda Čačinović - European career of a confrontational philosopher|work=[[Nacional (weekly)|Nacional]]|date=2007-05-08|accessdate=2011-11-27|language=Croatian|author=Nina Ožegović|archivedate=10 July 2012|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/693APLQP6}}</ref><ref name="ffzg-bio">{{cite web|url=http://www-wpt.ffzg.hr/filoz/nastavnici/nadezda-cacinovic/|title=Prof. dr. sc. Nadežda Čačinovič, red. prof.|publisher=Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences|language=Croatian|accessdate=2011-11-27}}</ref>
She was born to [[Slovenes|Slovene]] parents in [[Budapest]] in 1947 where her father Rudolf Čačinovič was serving as a military attache.<ref name="arhiva.nacional.hr">{{cite web|url=http://arhiva.nacional.hr/clanak/34133/nadezda-cacinovic-europska-karijera-borbene-filozofkinje|title=Nadežda Čačinovič - europska karijera borbene filozofkinje|website = Nacional |date= 8 May 2007|access-date=2 February 2016}}</ref> She graduated in philosophy and comparative literature at the [[University of Ljubljana]].<ref name="ffzg-bio"/> She subsequently studied at the University of Bonn from 1968 to 1970 where her father was serving as ambassador of Yugoslavia to West Germany. She obtained a doctorate and became a professor at the Department of Philosophy of the [[Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences]] at the University of Zagreb, being employed there since 1976.<ref name="nacional-2007"/><ref name="ffzg-bio"/>
She is also a member of an Advisory Board of a [[left-wing]] magazine ''[[Novi Plamen]]''. Čačinovič was also active in left wing politics, running for parliament for the [[Social Democratic Action of Croatia]].<ref name="arhiva.nacional.hr"/>
Since 2009 she has been the president of the Croatian P.E.N. Centre, member of [[International PEN]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.tportal.hr/kultura/knjizevnost/13364/Nadezda-cacinovic-nova-predsjednica-hrvatskog-P-E-N-a.html | publisher = T-portal | language = Croatian | title = Nadežda Čačinović nova predsjednica hrvatskog P.E.N.-a | date = 2009-03-09 | accessdate = 2011-11-29}}</ref>
After [[Andrea Zlatar-Violić]] became [[Ministry of Culture (Croatia)|Minister of Culture]] in the [[Croatian government]], Čačinovič was selected by Zlatar-Violić to take her place in the ministry's Committee for Books, Publication, and Bookselling Activities on 4 July 2012.<ref>[https://www.sukobinteresa.hr/sites/default/files/akti/2014/andreazlatarviolic-si-23-12.pdf Povjerenstvo za odlučivanje o sukobu interesa]</ref>
==Published books== *''Zašto čitati filozofe''. Zagreb, 2009. *''Vodič kroz svjetsku književnost za inteligentnu ženu''. Zagreb, 2007. *''Žene i filozofija''. Zagreb, 2006. *''Parvulla aesthetica''. Zagreb, 2004. *''Danilo Pejović, professor emeritus Facultatis philosophicae Universitatis studiorum Zagrabiensis''. Zagreb, 2002. *''U ženskom ključu''. Zagreb, 2000. *''Doba slika u teoriji mediologije''. Zagreb, 2001. *''Ogled o pismenosti''. Zagreb, 1994. *''Estetika''. Zagreb, 1988. *''Estetika njemačke romantike''. Zagreb, 1987. *''Pisanje i mišljenje''. Zagreb 1981. *''Subjekt kritičke teorije''. Zagreb, 1980.
